%N A396246 Triangle read by rows: T(n,m) is the number of ways to fill an m X n grid by using the numbers 1, 2, ..., m*n exactly once, so that 1 is the only entry which is the smallest both in its row and in its column, 1 <= m <= n.
%C A396246 An alternative formulation: T(n,m) is the number of ways to fill the cells in an m X n grid one by one, so that except the first one, each cell is in the same row or column as a previously filled cell.
%H A396246 L. Fang et al., <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jcta.2023.105776">Successive vertex orderings of fully regular graphs</a>, Journal of Combinatorial Theory, Series A, 199, 105776.
%H A396246 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/297385/number-of-collinear-ways-to-fill-a-grid">Number of collinear ways to fill a grid</a>
%H A396246 University of Szeged, <a href="https://www.math.u-szeged.hu/~mmaroti/schweitzer/schweitzer-2019-eng.pdf">Problems of the 2019 Miklós Schweitzer Memorial Competition in Mathematics</a>
%F A396246 T(n,m) = (m*n)!*m!*n!/(m+n-1)!.
%e A396246 Triangle begins:
%e A396246 n\m |   1       2            3                  4                        5
%e A396246 ----+---------------------------------------------------------------------
%e A396246   1 |   1
%e A396246   2 |   2      16
%e A396246   3 |   6     360       108864
%e A396246   4 |  24   16128     95800320      2391175987200
%e A396246   5 | 120 1209600 186810624000 173778714869760000 615524208068689920000000
%e A396246 For m = 2, n = 3, the filling
%e A396246   1 3 4
%e A396246   5 6 2
%e A396246 does not satisfy the condition because 2 is the smallest entry both in its row and in its column.
%e A396246 The filling
%e A396246   1 3 6
%e A396246   2 5 4
%e A396246 satisfies the condition.
%o A396246 (PARI) T(n,m) = (m*n)!*m!*n!/(m+n-1)!
%Y A396246 Cf. A000142.
%K A396246 nonn,tabl,easy
%O A396246 1,2
